In the {{ill|15th century|ja|15世紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōta Dōkan|ja|太田道灌|12=draft|12=draft}} was searching for a suitable hill to build a satellite castle for {{ill|Edo Castle|ja|江戸城|12=draft|12=draft}}. He found the {{ill|Kase Plateau|ja|加瀬台|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kaseyama) in present-day {{ill|Kawasaki, Kanagawa|ja|川崎市|12=draft|12=draft}} and spent the night there. During his sleep, he dreamt of a {{ill|white heron|ja|白鷺|12=draft|12=draft}} flying away with his helmet (kabuto) and dropping it after a while. Upon waking, Dōkan took this as an ill omen and abandoned his plans to build the castle on Kase Plateau. Since then, the plateau has been known as "Yumemigasaki" (Dream-Viewing Hill), and the spot where his helmet fell came to be called "Kabutozuka" (Helmet Mound), which corresponds to the current site of Kabutozuka Kofun.

