The cluster of kofun concentrated in {{ill|Komaoka, Yokohama|ja|駒岡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is known as the '''Komaoka Kofun Group''', which includes the {{ill|Komaoka Hyōtan-yama Kofun|ja|駒岡瓢箪山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Komaoka Dō-no-mae Kofun|ja|駒岡堂の前古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Iwaseyama Cave Tomb Group|ja|岩瀬山横穴墓群|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. 

Kabutozuka Kofun is located on a ridge to the east of the hills where the Komaoka Kofun Group is situated, at the northern end of the ridge. It is said that there were other kofun besides Kabutozuka in the area, collectively referred to as the '''Kajiyama Kofun Group'''. 

== Legend of Ōta Dōkan ==

In the {{ill|15th century|ja|15世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōta Dōkan|ja|太田道灌|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was searching for a suitable hill to build a satellite castle for {{ill|Edo Castle|ja|江戸城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. He found the {{ill|Kase Plateau|ja|加瀬台|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kaseyama) in present-day {{ill|Kawasaki, Kanagawa|ja|川崎市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and spent the night there. During his sleep, he dreamt of a {{ill|white heron|ja|白鷺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} flying away with his helmet (kabuto) and dropping it after a while. Upon waking, Dōkan took this as an ill omen and abandoned his plans to build the castle on Kase Plateau. Since then, the plateau has been known as "Yumemigasaki" (Dream-Viewing Hill), and the spot where his helmet fell came to be called "Kabutozuka" (Helmet Mound), which corresponds to the current site of Kabutozuka Kofun.

Although unrelated to this legend, the Kase Plateau in Kawasaki, where Dōkan abandoned his construction plans, contains the {{ill|Kasedai Kofun Group|ja|加瀬台古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (also known as the Yumemigasaki Kofun Group).

== Current Status ==

Kabutozuka has long been known as a site associated with the Dōkan legend. Excavations in 1931 and 1938 uncovered artifacts such as {{ill|magatama|ja|勾玉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, cut glass beads, and {{ill|earrings|ja|耳環|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, confirming that it is a 6th-century {{ill|circular tumulus (empun)|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with a diameter of 30.2 meters. Although most of the mound has been destroyed, a monument now stands in front of the remaining portion.

